-- The same thing, but with multiple casts in a row.
-- Because the first cast tends to be converted directly to a conversion function,
-- ORCA shouldn't be able to detect the first coercion and should require a redistribution.
explain (verbose, costs off) select * from cst_float4 as cst_float4_f join cst_float4 as cst_float4_s on cst_float4_f.a::int::float4 = cst_float4_s.a;
                                  QUERY PLAN                                   
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 Gather Motion 3:1  (slice1; segments: 3)
   Output: cst_float4_f.a, cst_float4_s.a
   ->  Hash Join
         Output: cst_float4_f.a, cst_float4_s.a
         Hash Cond: ((int4(cst_float4_f.a))::real = cst_float4_s.a)
         ->  Redistribute Motion 3:3  (slice2; segments: 3)
               Output: cst_float4_f.a
               Hash Key: (int4(cst_float4_f.a))::real
               ->  Seq Scan on public.cst_float4 cst_float4_f
                     Output: cst_float4_f.a
         ->  Hash
               Output: cst_float4_s.a
               ->  Seq Scan on public.cst_float4 cst_float4_s
                     Output: cst_float4_s.a
 Optimizer: GPORCA
 Settings: optimizer_enable_mergejoin = 'off', optimizer_enable_nljoin = 'off'
(16 rows)

